        "modified": "2019-08-05T20:06:27",
        "modified_gmt": "2019-08-05T20:06:27",
        "slug": "step-3-factor-your-savings-into-your-budget",
        "status": "publish",
        "type": "sfwd-lessons",
        "link": "https://community.tala.test/course/savings-101/lessons/step-3-factor-your-savings-into-your-budget/",
        "title": {
            "rendered": "Step 3: Factor your savings into your budget"
        },
        "content": {
            "rendered": "\n<p>To reach your savings goal, you‚Äôll have to be selective on how you spend your money on flexible expenses.<br></p>\n\n\n\n<p>Since the purpose to save is to achieve your goals, always set aside your money for savings first.&nbsp; Then budget your regular expenses (rent, etc.) and lastly determine how much you can spend on flexible expenses.&nbsp;<br></p>\n\n\n\n<p><strong>Tip #1:</strong> Be realistic! You may be able to cut down on eating out at restaurants or lower your grocery expenses by 20% by buying cheaper groceries, but don‚Äôt expect to cut your grocery bill by 80%.&nbsp;</p>\n\n\n\n<p><strong>Tip #2: </strong>Save where it counts! If you cannot meet your savings goals by cutting your flexible expenses, you might have to start exploring ways to save money on the big fixed expenses, like finding cheaper housing.&nbsp;It‚Äôs easy to look for small places to cut spending but you may have to adjust for big, fixed expenses, like moving to a cheaper area, to actually start saving.<br></p>\n\n\n\n<h3><strong>What expenses can you cut to save and achieve your goals?&nbsp;</strong></h3>\n\n\n\n<p><br>Share in the comments below! </p>\n",
            "protected": false
        },
