        "id": 255,
        "date": "2019-08-01T08:50:48",
        "date_gmt": "2019-08-01T08:50:48",
        "guid": {
            "rendered": "https://community.tala.test/lessons/lesson/"
        },
        "modified": "2019-08-05T20:07:19",
        "modified_gmt": "2019-08-05T20:07:19",
        "slug": "step-4-determine-where-you-want-to-place-your-savings",
        "status": "publish",
        "type": "sfwd-lessons",
        "link": "https://community.tala.test/course/savings-101/lessons/step-4-determine-where-you-want-to-place-your-savings/",
        "title": {
            "rendered": "Step 4: Determine where you want to place your savings"
        },
        "content": {
            "rendered": "\n<p>Carrying around a big wad of savings can be risky. Instead, put your savings in a trusted institution that works best for you. Here are a few options that might work well:&nbsp;<br></p>\n\n\n\n<p style=\"text-align:center\">üíµ</p>\n\n\n\n<h4 style=\"text-align:center\">A <strong><span style=\"text-decoration: underline;\">savings account</span></strong> is a deposit account at a bank that earns higher interest than a checking account.&nbsp;</h4>\n\n\n\n<p><span style=\"text-decoration: underline;\">PRO</span>: It is a separate account from your general pool of money so you can ensure that you‚Äôre not using it for daily needs. Banks are highly regulated so your money and personal identity are safe. There is proper documentation to ensure transparency and accountability.&nbsp;</p>\n\n\n\n<p><br><span style=\"text-decoration: underline;\">CON</span>: There may be fees or minimums to open up an account. Some banks require that you physically go to their branches, which may be limited depending on where you live. Some banks have limits on how much you can take out of your savings account each month. The interest rates are low to none, depending on the bank.&nbsp;<br></p>\n\n\n\n<p style=\"text-align:center\">üíµ</p>\n\n\n\n<h4 style=\"text-align:center\">A<strong> <span style=\"text-decoration: underline;\">chama</span></strong> is an informal, self-organized merry-go-round cash contribution and table banking group. <br></h4>\n\n\n\n<p><span style=\"text-decoration: underline;\">PRO</span>: Chamas can be formed by at least three people who know each other, so trust is high. Members have a direct say on chama matters in regular meetings and they can invest as a group to grow their finances.&nbsp;<br></p>\n\n\n\n<p><span style=\"text-decoration: underline;\">CON</span>: There are no laws that protect chama members or their finances. There are no standard rules for chamas ‚Äî each will be different according to those members. Personal differences can interfere with official chama proceedings. Scheduling across all the members can be difficult at times.&nbsp;<br></p>\n\n\n\n<p style=\"text-align:center\">üíµ</p>\n\n\n\n<h4 style=\"text-align:center\">A <strong><span style=\"text-decoration: underline;\">sacco</span> </strong>is a savings and lending group organized around a common interest <br>(ex. Farmers Sacco, Teachers Sacco, etc.)&nbsp;</h4>\n\n\n\n<p><span style=\"text-decoration: underline;\">PRO:</span> With a sacco, your can have access&nbsp; to loans depending on one‚Äôs savings. One can own shares and earn from them.&nbsp;<br></p>\n\n\n\n<p><span style=\"text-decoration: underline;\">CON</span>:¬† You need a guarantor to access a loan. Some saccos have poor communications due to expansion. There is limited regulation on saccos, meaning limited consumer protection and potential for fraud. There are also many different types of saccos in the market so it requires some research to know what is best for you.¬†<br></p>\n\n\n\n<h3><strong>Where will you save your money?¬†</strong></h3>\n\n\n\n<p>Tell us in the comments below! </p>\n",
            "protected": false
        },
